<br>
Other people are also free to have their religious beliefs, too.<br>
<br>
When religious beliefs are forced upon people, their right to religious expression is violated.<br>
<br>
Using the goverment as a tool to spread a specific religious message is a violation of the right to religious freedom.  It is contrary to what the founding fathers believed.  It is contrary to what the initial colonists of the United States believed.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>In deciding most cases, the Supreme Court has applied the &quot;Lemon Test,&quot; from the Lemon vs. Kurtzman decision of 1971, which requires that all government activity:<br>
-- Must serve a principally secular purpose.<br>
-- Must not, in effect, advance religion over non-religion.<br>
-- Must not involve excessive entanglement with religion.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Clearly, this is much more than merely forbidding the governmental establishment of any particular religion.<br>
<br>
What you believe is irrelevant, but you have the right to believe anything you want. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2159<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/2/03 3:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=123>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Freedom of Religion</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>When religious beliefs are forced upon people, their right to religious expression is violated.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Exactly.  That is the problem.  The rights of people of any religion but atheism are being violated as the government attempts to force atheism on us in certain arenas (like courthouses).<br>
<br>
BTW, I don't think that the 10 commandments monument did violate the Lemon Test from reading it in your blurb there.  It's my first exposure to the idea though.<br>
<br>
Janus, the problem in that case is that a religion was being forced upon her.  That's exactly what I'm fighting against.  I don't want the government to support any religion, whether it be Christianity, Atheism, or Islam, over any other religion.  They should all be equal in the eyes of the law.  If by secular you mean atheist, I don't support a secular government.  I support a government that views all religions equally, not a government that favors atheism.<br>
<br>
Seeing an item representing one religion or another is not forcing that religion on someone.  By that definition, a person wearing a cross or star of david on a necklace around his or her neck would be attempting to force his/her religion on everyone that saw it.  It's an absurd argument.<br>
<br>
