<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I would not vote to convict even if it were clear that he was guilty -- Ammelen, October 2, 2003<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Please clarify these conflicting statements.<br>
<br>
Since you have admitted that outside bias would cause you to ignore the law when determining guilt (and as a result, Justice) ... why do you find it difficult to comprehend that others would use religion to ignore the law as well?<br>
<br>
When a juror convicts or acquits the accused by ignorig the evidence, and instead uses their own personal religious or philosophical system, Justice is not served.  The victims and the accused are the ones with the problem -- not the juror.<br>
<br>
If you disagree with the law then elect different representatives.  Or move to a place with laws you agree with? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2163<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/2/03 9:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=115.topic&index=133>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Freedom of Religion</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Please clarify these conflicting statements.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I actually explained it in the post you quoted that from.  Essentially, I would exercise the power of judicial review.  If I believed that a law that were passed violated the Constitution, I would not vote to convict on it.  I never said that I wouldn't vote to convict someone because a law differed from my religious views.<br>
<br>
I would actually choose not to serve on a jury if it were a conflict with my religious beliefs.  For example, I oppose the death penalty in all cases.  Thus, I would simply not serve on a jury where such a decision were needed.<br>
